{"author":{"id":"c52cb19fb02c210e51792121b2bae318d19fa8efb308ae796946bf1f79891ad1"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1783147039,"nonce":"cX+Cg9kwRd+XyeD3xlJtUggCSco=","message":"Shipped in PR #74 (squash 4f27c41). SQLite view rendering is no longer deferred.\n\nStated scope â€” all done:\n- Dialect seams honored by the shared view renderer: `qualify_schema` (schema suppression for schema-less backends), the `unary_string_fn_name` seam reused for scalar functions (`length`, not `CHAR_LENGTH`), and `substring_uses_function_call` (`substr(...)`) â€” the seams already existed on `SqliteDialect`; the view renderer now consults them.\n- `render_create` renders views (last, in dependency order); `render_plan` renders CreateView/DropView. The `Unsupported` deferral errors are gone.\n- Cross-backend view render tests, plus SQLite-specific ones.\n\nWent beyond the original scope to make the feature actually correct end-to-end (driven by a thorough Codex review â€” 9 distinct findings, each fixed with a regression test):\n- **View introspection**: SQLite now reads views back from `sqlite_master` (name + column names, `Bytes` sentinel type) so a removed/renamed view produces a `DropView` instead of lingering, and views take part in the one-namespace collision check.\n- **Destructive-change policy**: via a `canonical_view_column_type` override (uniform `Bytes`), the diff compares view columns by name â€” an unchanged view (computed columns included) re-applies non-destructively (passes `BLOCK_RISKY`), a column-set change is a blocked destructive `DropView` (matching PostgreSQL). This let the earlier core-diff guard be reverted, so the only shared-core change is the additive view-render seam wiring.\n- **Plan ordering / name transitions**: views are dropped up front (before a table rebuild renames a table under a live view â€” SQLite errors on the reparse otherwise); the view pre-drop runs after table drops and skips names a table still owns (dropped or renamed away, case-folded) so tableâ†”view replacements and rename-reuses-name all apply cleanly.\n- **Broken views**: an un-analyzable view (its table dropped out of band, or an unregistered function) no longer fails the whole introspection â€” it falls back to name-only so it can still be dropped.\n\nDeferred (tracked in **6a3940a**): the view-replan churn (a body-unknown view re-applies every plan, since the core diff can't compare bodies and SQLite has no `CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW`) and the consequent `INSTEAD OF` trigger loss on re-apply. The real fix is executor-side trigger capture/replay plus body-aware view comparison to stop the re-apply firing on unchanged views â€” its own slice. squealy has no trigger model, so those triggers are out-of-band objects.\n\nClosing: all stated scope complete; the one deferral is tracked separately.","files":null}]}